Action on D-branes   
Next, let us consider induced actions on D-branes in orbifolds.

In general terms, orbifold group actions on the  field necessarily
mix with orbifold group actions on D-branes because of the relationship
between gauge transformations of the  field and affine translations
of the Chan-Paton factors.  As is well-known, for consistency,
under a gauge transformation ,
the Chan-Paton gauge fields necessarily undergo an affine
translation .  As a result, since orbifold group
actions on  fields in general mix group actions on the base space
with gauge transformations of the  field, they also act nontrivially
on Chan-Paton factors, and hence on D-branes.

In we described orbifold group actions on D-branes
for the most general possible orbifold group action on the  field.
Assuming for simplicity that the  field is topologically trivial,
we can write the most general orbifold group action as
* 
where  defines an action on the Chan-Paton factors,
and  denotes the identity matrix.

In the case of ordinary discrete torsion, recall again that the
bundles  were trivial, the connections  gauge-trivial,
and the connection-preserving bundle maps  become
constants defining the group cocycles.  In this case, the expression
above simplifies to become
* 
which just describes a projectivized orbifold group action on the D-brane
worldvolume, precisely as predicted in.

Next, consider the case of toroidal orbifolds and our non-discrete-torsion
degrees of freedom.  Here, again the bundles  are trivial,
as all flat bundles on a torus are trivial, and we have turned off
discrete torsion so that all the  are trivial,
but the  are still nontrivial, and so we obtain
* 
Put another way, under the action of the orbifold group,
instead of projectivizing the orbifold group action as in
, instead the orbifold group maps 
the bundle .
Because the bundles  obey the group law in the appropriate sense,
this orbifold group action is an honest orbifold group action, and not
a projectivized action.

Note in hindsight that our result can be derived much more simply
(and much more loosely) from the general idea that 
gauge transformations that rotate the
period of the  field by  are equivalent to tensoring the
D-brane bundles with some line bundle.
Thus, the fact that we are seeing these orbifold degrees of freedom
involving nonzero gauge fields 's correspond to 
tensoring D-brane bundles should not be a surprise.



In passing, note that we are not  merely making an ansatz
that D-brane actions have such a form; rather, we are recovering
these D-brane actions as a special case of the general first-principles
derivation
presented in.  











First consistency check:  Douglas's calculation  
In, a calculation was performed
to check the consistency of the D-brane orbifold group
realization of discrete torsion, with
the usual closed-string twisted sector phases of.

In this calculation, one takes a Riemann surface with boundary,
and evaluates the Wilson loop along the boundary.  The evaluation of
that Wilson loop will pick up a phase, as determined by the orbifold
group action on the D-branes, and for consistency, the total phase
one gets should be the same as for the corresponding closed-string
twisted sector.


 
