  spectrum computation 


To help illustrate these degrees of freedom, we will consider
the example of .
In this example, combining the orbifold group action with
momentum shifts will have no effect - the new orbifold CFT
is isomorphic to the original orbifold CFT.
However, this example will provide us with the opportunity to explore
spectrum computations in some detail.

Note that it is not possible to turn on ordinary
discrete torsion in this orbifold: 
 
However, our momentum shift degrees of freedom are not counted by
, and they can  be turned on in .

To specify these momentum shift degrees of freedom, we must specify
a flat  gauge field on the covering space 
for each element of the orbifold group,
such that the gauge fields obey the group law.
Now, we can specify such gauge fields by their holonomies around
four cycles on , and for those holonomies to obey the group
law simply means that their square must be trivial.
Thus, the possible holonomies around each circle are zero and
 (in conventions where the circles have circumference 1).

In passing, note that since we are discussing symmetric  orbifolds,
level-matching should be satisfied automatically.  We will not discuss
level-matching further.

Now, we would like to understand the orbifold group action on the
states of the theory.  
In a symmetric orbifold, the possible phases  on
